  "prompt": "What does namespace mean in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, the concept of a \"namespace\" is not explicitly defined in the same way it is in some other programming languages, but it can be understood in the context of how Java organizes classes, interfaces, and packages.\n\n1. **Packages:** In Java, namespaces are primarily implemented through **packages**. A package is a namespace that organizes a set of related classes and interfaces. By grouping classes into packages, Java helps avoid naming conflicts. For example, you can have two classes named `List` in different packages (e.g., `java.util.List` and `java.awt.List`) without conflict because they're in separate namespaces.\n\n2. **Import Statements:** When using classes from different packages, you typically use an import statement at the beginning of your Java file to bring those classes into the current file\u2019s namespace. For instance:\n   ```java\n   import java.util.List;\n   ```\n\n3. **Qualified names:** If two classes have the same name but belong to different packages, you can refer to them using their fully qualified class names. For example:\n   ```java\n   java.util.List myList = new java.util.ArrayList();\n   java.awt.List myAWTList = new java.awt.List();\n   ```\n\n4. **Types of Namespaces:** Java's namespace system can be thought of in terms of different scopes, which include:\n   - **Package Scope:** Classes within the same package can access each other\u2019s package-private and public members.\n   - **Class Scope:** Inside a class, you have access to its own members (fields and methods).\n   - **Method Scope:** Inside methods, you can refer to local variables and parameters.\n\nIn summary, while Java does not have a direct \"namespace\" keyword or construct like some other programming languages (e.g., C++), it utilizes packages to create distinct namespaces that help manage the organization and accessibility of classes and interfaces.",
